Not Just in Transit: Drugs, the State and Society in West Africa | Center on International Cooperation                            Skip to main content                                                                  RSS   Email Updates                  Search form      Search                                    Main menu Home About People Publications Topics Regions Programs Blog Media & Events                                       Not Just in Transit: Drugs, the State and Society in West Africa                   In West Africa, civil wars have receded, democracy has gained ground and economies are growing. But a destructive new threat is jeopardizing this progress: with local collusion, international drug cartels are undermining our countries and communities, and devastating lives.   After looking at the evidence, consulting experts from the region and around the world, and visiting some of the most affected countries and communities in the region, the West Africa Commission on Drugs has reached a number of conclusions – detailed in this report, drafted by CIC Fellow Camino Kavanagh and Lansana Gberie – about how the problems of drug trafficking and consumption should be tacked.   Read the report Not Just in Transit in English or Pas seulement une zone de transit in French. Twisted and charred debris of a burnt-out Boeing 727 lie in the desert some 200 kilometres (125 miles) north of Gao in the northeast of the impoverished west African country on the southern edge of the Sahara on December 10, 2009. UN authorities said the plane transported cocaine from Venezuela to the west African country. According to the UN Office on Drugs and Crime, the Boeing 727 landed on a makeshift airstrip and unloaded a cargo of illegal drugs before crashing as it tried to take off.
